Here’s a short set of **responsive‑display adjustments** you can tack onto the same page:

```html
<style>
  /* Base mobile‑friendly rules */
  body {
    font-family: Lato, sans-serif;
    color: #333;
    margin: 0.5rem;
  }

  label, select {
    font-size: 1rem;
    display: block;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  a {
    color: #2C6670;
    text-decoration: underline;
    /* Finger‑friendly tap targets: */
    padding: 0.35em 0.4em;
    display: inline-block;
  }

  /* Hotline blocks */
  .hotline {
    background-color: #E0F2F4;
    border: 1px solid #2C6670;
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 0.75rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
  }

  /* Make text readable but compact on small screens */
  @media (max-width: 600px) {
    body { font-size: 1.05rem; }
    a { font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .hotline { padding: 1rem; }
  }

  /* Optional dark‑mode variant for mobile */
  @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
    body { background-color: #1E2D31; color: #E0F2F4; }
    .hotline {
      background-color: #2C6670;
      border-color: #A7C4A0;
    }
    a { color: #A7C4A0; }
  }
</style>
```

**Practical notes**

- `padding` around links ensures thumbs can tap without hitting adjacent text.  
- The `@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)` block honors mobile dark‑mode settings automatically.  
- Keep hotlines separated by borders rather than pure color so contrast changes don’t hide boundaries.  
- Maintain the ethical and accessibility line visible at the bottom in both light and dark themes.

These tweaks make your handout or webpage readable and easy to navigate across devices while keeping the core message—**warm support that guides people toward professional help**—clear everywhere.

